e notion of French exceptionalism is deeply embedded in the nation's self-image and in a range of political and academic discourses. Recently, the debate about whether France really is "exceptional" has acquired a critical edge. Against the background of introspection about the nature of "national identity," some proclaim "normalisation" and the end of French exceptionalism, while others point out to the continuing evidence that France remains distinctive at a number of levels, from popular culture to public policy. This book explores the notion of French exceptionalism, places it in its European context, examines its history and evaluate its continuing relevance in a range of fields from politics and public policy to popular culture and sport.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aFrench. 0aNational characteristics, French. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBell, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChafer, Tony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClift, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollard, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodin, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodin, Emmanuel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHewlett, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhn, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMajumdar, Margaret A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMignon, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab